40|$|Developing nations {{seeking to}} apply the Basel Convention on the Control of Transboundary Movements in Hazardous Wastes to prevent toxic ships from {{entering}} their waters for shipbreaking are faced with legal uncertainty. This paper responds to that uncertainty by adopting a {{definition of the offence}} of illegal traffic in end-of-life ships, and further proposing <b>evidentiary</b> <b>burdens</b> and potential sources of proof for that offence. While a shipowner's intention to scrap a ship for its value in steel was previously difficult to prove, recent market analysis of the shipbreaking industry provides potential proof sufficient to halt the importation of a toxic ship. Shipbreaking Basel Convention Illegal traffic Toxic ships...|$|R
